WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.273 --> 00:00:03.289
<i>Previously on "Designated Survivor"...</i>

2
00:00:03.292 --> 00:00:04.601
It's about the NATO summit.

3
00:00:04.604 --> 00:00:07.176
The new French ambassador
wanted to talk about nukes.

4
00:00:07.179 --> 00:00:08.788
It's an opening to De-escalate.

5
00:00:08.824 --> 00:00:11.184
There's enough explosives in
here to blow up three Capitols.

6
00:00:11.193 --> 00:00:13.120
- [Muffled shouting]
- Tom: She's been kidnapped.

7
00:00:13.123 --> 00:00:14.816
Foerstel: She was looking
into Browning Reed.

8
00:00:14.818 --> 00:00:16.895
Agent Wells is convinced that
the ex-C.E.O. Patrick Lloyd's

9
00:00:16.897 --> 00:00:18.297
involved with the conspiracy.

10
00:00:18.333 --> 00:00:20.099
I'm brooming any connection between you.

11
00:00:20.135 --> 00:00:21.900
Browning Reed. and the Capitol mission.

12
00:00:21.936 --> 00:00:23.902
<i>Soon. there'll be no
paper trail whatsoever.</i>

13
00:00:23.938 --> 00:00:25.723
<i>and Agent Wells is contained.</i>

14
00:00:25.726 --> 00:00:27.773
Abe Leonard has eaten up
everything I've fed him.

15
00:00:27.775 --> 00:00:29.108
When are we gonna see
something from him. then?

16
00:00:29.110 --> 00:00:30.174
Any day. I expect.

17
00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:31.610
[Silenced gunshots]

18
00:00:32.613 --> 00:00:34.679
Since the attack at the Capitol.

19
00:00:34.715 --> 00:00:36.851
references to Browning
Reed have been deleted.

20
00:00:36.854 --> 00:00:38.850
If we find out who
deleted these files...

21
00:00:38.886 --> 00:00:40.118
we find our traitor.

22
00:00:40.154 --> 00:00:42.921
[Both grunting]

23
00:00:42.957 --> 00:00:44.957
[Breathing heavily]

24
00:00:51.465 --> 00:00:54.298
Man on P.A.: <i>Be advised.
All security teams...</i>

25
00:00:54.334 --> 00:00:56.634
[Indistinct shouting]

26
00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:58.936
[Man on P.A. speaking indistinctly]

27
00:01:02.775 --> 00:01:04.808
[Shouting in distance]

28
00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:22.258
[Gasps]

29
00:01:22.294 --> 00:01:24.260
[Indistinct shouting]

30
00:01:35.373 --> 00:01:37.540
[Indistinct conversations]

31
00:01:54.161 --> 00:02:00.078
- <font color="#D81D1D">Synced and corrected by VitoSilans</font> -
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.Addic7ed.com</font> --

32
00:02:06.838 --> 00:02:10.272
[Seth groans. coughs]

33
00:02:11.475 --> 00:02:12.640
Hey. Seth. you okay?

34
00:02:12.676 --> 00:02:13.842
[Toilet flushes]

35
00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:17.759
Yeah. I'm sorry. Uh. I-I
don't know what's happening.

36
00:02:17.762 --> 00:02:19.060
I-I don't usually get airsick.

37
00:02:19.063 --> 00:02:19.938
Oh.

38
00:02:19.941 --> 00:02:22.718
And to think. it's your first
time on<i> Air Force One.</i> too.

39
00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:25.586
- Hey. Seth. look.
- [Camera shutter clicks]

40
00:02:25.622 --> 00:02:27.822
[Chuckles] You can send
this one to your mom. as well.

41
00:02:27.858 --> 00:02:29.990
[Vomiting. coughing]

42
00:02:30.026 --> 00:02:31.592
Time to rally. son.

43
00:02:31.628 --> 00:02:33.861
We got to gaggle with
the press before we land.

44
00:02:33.897 --> 00:02:35.830
[Vomits]

45
00:02:43.038 --> 00:02:45.305
[Knock on door]

46
00:02:45.341 --> 00:02:47.374
Yes.

47
00:02:47.410 --> 00:02:48.975
Bad time?

48
00:02:49.011 --> 00:02:50.911
No. Come on in.

49
00:02:52.181 --> 00:02:53.847
I. uh...

50
00:02:53.883 --> 00:02:56.003
I think the pressure of his
first international summit

51
00:02:56.018 --> 00:02:58.551
may have gotten to your press secretary.

52
00:02:58.587 --> 00:03:00.386
And I just wondered how<i> you're</i> doing.

53
00:03:00.422 --> 00:03:01.855
I'm fine. Is Seth all right?

54
00:03:01.891 --> 00:03:04.657
Yeah. just a case of the jitters.

55
00:03:04.693 --> 00:03:06.525
He'll get over it as soon as he realizes

56
00:03:06.561 --> 00:03:08.194
that a NATO summit is no different

57
00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:09.796
than an outsized cabinet meeting

58
00:03:09.832 --> 00:03:11.231
in a lot of different languages.

59
00:03:11.267 --> 00:03:12.398
[Both chuckle]

60
00:03:12.434 --> 00:03:15.033
I hope it's that simple.

61
00:03:15.069 --> 00:03:17.029
Are they gonna think that
it's presumptuous of me.

62
00:03:17.038 --> 00:03:18.671
putting an initiative on the table?

63
00:03:18.707 --> 00:03:22.040
Hell no. You're the president
of the United States.

64
00:03:22.076 --> 00:03:24.209
Right. [Chuckles softly]

65
00:03:24.245 --> 00:03:26.011
I know I'm not the
negotiator that you are...

66
00:03:26.047 --> 00:03:27.713
Ah. don't sell yourself short.

67
00:03:27.749 --> 00:03:30.549
You know. we may have
different styles. Tom.

68
00:03:30.585 --> 00:03:33.051
but I think that's what
makes us a good team.

69
00:03:33.087 --> 00:03:35.053
The professor and the politician.

70
00:03:35.089 --> 00:03:36.191
[Chuckles]

71
00:03:36.222 --> 00:03:38.557
You give them the facts.
and I'll twist their arms.

72
00:03:38.559 --> 00:03:40.625
That works for me.

73
00:03:40.661 --> 00:03:43.495
I know how important this is to you.

74
00:03:44.997 --> 00:03:46.763
Yeah.

75
00:03:46.766 --> 00:03:50.201
The arms control was going to
be a priority of my second term.

76
00:03:51.271 --> 00:03:53.605
Well... now it's<i> our</i> priority.

77
00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:58.876
Foerstel: I don't care
about your overtime.

78
00:03:58.912 --> 00:04:01.307
- No. you search everywhere...
- [Keypad beeps. door opens]

79
00:04:01.310 --> 00:04:03.748
and then when you've done
that. search it again.

80
00:04:03.784 --> 00:04:05.216
[Computers beeping]

81
00:04:05.252 --> 00:04:06.256
Still nothing?

82
00:04:06.303 --> 00:04:09.921
No. I got every agency
in the country looking.

83
00:04:09.957 --> 00:04:11.522
She knows how to take care of herself.

84
00:04:11.558 --> 00:04:12.933
Yeah.

85
00:04:12.956 --> 00:04:15.126
Where are you with the
Browning Reed investigation?

86
00:04:15.128 --> 00:04:16.768
I got Chuck Russink
coming in to help out.

87
00:04:16.796 --> 00:04:19.596
Russink? You serious?
He's a space cadet.

88
00:04:19.632 --> 00:04:21.165
Hannah trusts him.

89
00:04:22.235 --> 00:04:24.034
Whatever it takes. I guess.

90
00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:26.069
Victor: I was gonna pay. Ms. Rhodes.

91
00:04:26.105 --> 00:04:27.604
No. seriously. I'll get it.

92
00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:29.507
Where's our server?

93
00:04:34.581 --> 00:04:36.213
Will you guys excuse me a second?

94
00:04:36.249 --> 00:04:37.747
Yeah.

95
00:04:37.783 --> 00:04:38.949
What?

96
00:04:41.820 --> 00:04:43.153
Hey. you.

97
00:04:43.189 --> 00:04:44.420
Hey. Hey.

98
00:04:44.456 --> 00:04:47.324
How you doing? It's good to see you.

99
00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:50.827
Oh. oh. Emily Rhodes. meet
my cousin. Nadia Espinosa.

100
00:04:50.863 --> 00:04:52.329
It's a pleasure.

101
00:04:52.365 --> 00:04:54.831
Hi. You work for
Congresswoman Yoshida. right?

102
00:04:54.867 --> 00:04:56.666
That's right.

103
00:04:56.702 --> 00:04:58.868
- How's that going?
- I love it.

104
00:04:58.904 --> 00:05:02.037
I mean. it's great to be able
to collaborate with good people.

105
00:05:02.073 --> 00:05:04.106
Wow. Are you sure you two are related?

106
00:05:04.142 --> 00:05:05.274
[Both chuckle]

107
00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:06.676
Yeah. I wonder all the time.

108
00:05:08.803 --> 00:05:11.246
I need another beer. Do
you guys want anything?

109
00:05:11.249 --> 00:05:12.883
- No. I'm good. thanks.
- No. thank you.

110
00:05:12.886 --> 00:05:14.116
[Clears throat]

111
00:05:14.152 --> 00:05:16.385
[Sighs] So. POTUS is
heading up to Toronto.

112
00:05:16.421 --> 00:05:18.120
Yes. The White House is all mine.

113
00:05:18.156 --> 00:05:20.689
[Chuckles] No. seriously.
it's his first NATO summit.

114
00:05:20.725 --> 00:05:22.324
First time out of the country.

115
00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:23.658
Polls are high.

116
00:05:23.694 --> 00:05:25.660
I mean. he's on a roll. So are you.

117
00:05:25.696 --> 00:05:27.763
I do have to admit. it feels good.

118
00:05:27.799 --> 00:05:30.331
What about you? Are you
gonna follow Hookstraten?

119
00:05:30.367 --> 00:05:32.768
No. she did offer. but. uh...

120
00:05:32.804 --> 00:05:35.637
I don't see myself working
for the Secretary of Education.

121
00:05:35.673 --> 00:05:37.241
It's not exactly the fast lane.

122
00:05:37.244 --> 00:05:39.141
Let's just say. after
you work in the West Wing.

123
00:05:39.143 --> 00:05:41.109
everything feels like a step down.

124
00:05:41.145 --> 00:05:43.111
Well. just so you know.

125
00:05:43.147 --> 00:05:45.446
I was not opposed to
Hookstraten for V.P.

126
00:05:45.482 --> 00:05:48.056
I think it would've been great
to be working together again.

127
00:05:48.059 --> 00:05:49.183
Yeah. it would've been.

128
00:05:49.219 --> 00:05:51.519
It's Washington. Anything
can happen. right?

129
00:05:51.555 --> 00:05:54.222
And it usually does.

130
00:05:54.258 --> 00:05:55.890
Yeah.

131
00:05:55.926 --> 00:05:57.825
I should get back.

132
00:05:57.861 --> 00:06:00.294
Thanks for stopping by.

133
00:06:01.197 --> 00:06:03.898
♪ ♪

134
00:06:05.635 --> 00:06:08.235
[Sirens wail]

135
00:06:12.208 --> 00:06:15.776
So. we attend the general
reception for 30 minutes.

136
00:06:15.812 --> 00:06:17.344
smile for the cameras.

137
00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:19.679
then we retreat to a hospitality suite

138
00:06:19.715 --> 00:06:23.683
I set up for select members
of the Nuclear Planning Group.

139
00:06:23.719 --> 00:06:25.752
That gives us a chance
to start some lobbying

140
00:06:25.788 --> 00:06:27.921
- before the general session.
- Smart.

141
00:06:27.957 --> 00:06:29.900
Well. it's not my first rodeo. son.

142
00:06:29.903 --> 00:06:30.947
[Chuckles]

143
00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:32.692
Now. our primary target

144
00:06:32.728 --> 00:06:35.728
is French Prime
Minister Justine Massett.

145
00:06:35.764 --> 00:06:39.332
Sharp as a tack and as
chauvinistic as Joan of Arc.

146
00:06:39.368 --> 00:06:42.335
She can be very prickly.

147
00:06:42.371 --> 00:06:44.350
Why would she be? It was
the French who wanted us

148
00:06:44.353 --> 00:06:46.172
to bring up arms reduction
in the first place.

149
00:06:46.208 --> 00:06:49.408
Yes. Privately.

150
00:06:49.444 --> 00:06:51.077
But in front of NATO.

151
00:06:51.113 --> 00:06:53.579
the French want us to bring
up the initiative first.

152
00:06:53.615 --> 00:06:56.082
giving them an opportunity to criticize

153
00:06:56.118 --> 00:06:58.017
or even withdraw. if they so choose.

154
00:06:58.053 --> 00:07:00.286
It's all part of the game...

155
00:07:00.322 --> 00:07:02.162
Don't stick your neck
out if you don't have to.

156
00:07:03.191 --> 00:07:05.391
Then there's Jonas Grottke.

157
00:07:05.427 --> 00:07:08.226
just re-elected as German Chancellor.

158
00:07:08.262 --> 00:07:11.229
He's also a chairman of
NATO's Nuclear Planning Group.

159
00:07:11.265 --> 00:07:13.565
Strong ally. Got you covered there.

160
00:07:13.601 --> 00:07:15.901
Good. One less thing
for me to worry about.

161
00:07:15.937 --> 00:07:19.004
The one unknown to me is Aruna Mahajan.

162
00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:22.773
The first British Indian
prime minister in U.K. history.

163
00:07:22.809 --> 00:07:27.078
Fiercely independent but
was able to forge a coalition

164
00:07:27.114 --> 00:07:30.081
and under extremely
turbulent conditions.

165
00:07:30.117 --> 00:07:31.949
Well. we have something in common.

166
00:07:31.985 --> 00:07:33.051
True enough.

167
00:07:33.087 --> 00:07:35.153
I can work with that.

168
00:07:35.189 --> 00:07:36.721
What?

169
00:07:36.757 --> 00:07:38.524
Thank you.

170
00:07:40.027 --> 00:07:42.293
♪ ♪

171
00:07:45.832 --> 00:07:48.199
[Indistinct conversations]

172
00:07:51.772 --> 00:07:54.138
[<i>Radio chatter</i>]

173
00:08:07.287 --> 00:08:09.987
[<i>Radio chatter continues</i>]

174
00:08:11.291 --> 00:08:12.489
Hey.

175
00:08:14.994 --> 00:08:19.295
Mayday. mayday. This is FBI
Agent Hannah Wells. Mayday.

176
00:08:19.331 --> 00:08:21.464
Hannah: <i>FBI Agent Hannah Wells. Mayday.</i>

177
00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:23.934
<i>Mayday. This is... Hannah Wells.</i>

178
00:08:23.970 --> 00:08:27.136
- [Static crackling]
- <i>Hannah Wells.</i> this is

179
00:08:27.172 --> 00:08:29.672
Coast Guard Station 142. Indian River.

180
00:08:29.708 --> 00:08:32.873
[Static crackles]

181
00:08:32.876 --> 00:08:34.875
Coast Guard Station 142

182
00:08:34.878 --> 00:08:36.511
calling the ship <i>Hannah Wells.</i>

183
00:08:36.514 --> 00:08:37.947
[Static crackles]

184
00:08:37.983 --> 00:08:39.811
This is FBI Agent Hannah Wells.

185
00:08:39.858 --> 00:08:41.658
- [Door opens]
- Mayda...

186
00:08:46.057 --> 00:08:47.323
[<i>Radio chatter</i>]

187
00:08:59.604 --> 00:09:01.437
Unh!

188
00:09:11.028 --> 00:09:13.778
Tom: To begin. I want to
thank you all for being here.

189
00:09:13.781 --> 00:09:17.331
As you know. in addition to
tomorrow's regular schedule.

190
00:09:17.334 --> 00:09:19.934
the United States will be
introducing an initiative

191
00:09:19.937 --> 00:09:22.337
that would reduce
NATO's nuclear arsenal.

192
00:09:22.340 --> 00:09:23.834
Now. I want to be absolutely clear

193
00:09:23.870 --> 00:09:25.836
that this is a proposed
weapons-reduction change.

194
00:09:25.872 --> 00:09:27.504
not a change in doctrine.

195
00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:30.707
And it's entirely predicated
upon the Russian Federation

196
00:09:30.743 --> 00:09:34.111
scaling back its
strategic nuclear weapons

197
00:09:34.147 --> 00:09:37.180
in proportional response
to NATO's actions.

198
00:09:37.216 --> 00:09:38.715
something that the Russian president

199
00:09:38.751 --> 00:09:41.317
has assured me he is ready to do.

200
00:09:41.353 --> 00:09:43.186
What. you believe him. Cornelius?

201
00:09:43.222 --> 00:09:44.554
Yeah. I do.

202
00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:45.888
On what basis?

203
00:09:45.924 --> 00:09:48.491
On the basis of our 20-year relationship

204
00:09:48.527 --> 00:09:51.394
and being able to tell when
he's lying and when he's not.

205
00:09:51.430 --> 00:09:53.530
[Laughter]

206
00:09:53.566 --> 00:09:57.066
And based on the fact that it
is in the interest of all sides

207
00:09:57.102 --> 00:09:59.368
to agree on anything that will lead

208
00:09:59.404 --> 00:10:02.013
to a more stable and secure planet.

209
00:10:02.016 --> 00:10:05.150
Despite recent disruptions
to the world order.

210
00:10:05.186 --> 00:10:09.254
this is not the time to retreat
into isolationism or populism.

211
00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:12.657
This is the time to show
that global cooperation

212
00:10:12.693 --> 00:10:14.992
can and will lead us to a safer future.

213
00:10:15.028 --> 00:10:18.029
Not to mention that the way
that we keep our nuclear arsenals

214
00:10:18.065 --> 00:10:19.598
is insanely expensive.

215
00:10:21.001 --> 00:10:23.535
It's intriguing. Mr. President.

216
00:10:23.571 --> 00:10:26.871
but Poland and Slovakia have
no nuclear weapons of our own.

217
00:10:26.907 --> 00:10:29.641
We rely on your American
nuclear umbrellas.

218
00:10:29.677 --> 00:10:33.411
So what can you offer
by way of a guarantee

219
00:10:33.447 --> 00:10:37.548
that our peace and our safety
will still be protected?

220
00:10:38.751 --> 00:10:43.720
The closest thing I can offer
to a guarantee is my word.

221
00:10:43.756 --> 00:10:45.389
not as Tom Kirkman.

222
00:10:45.425 --> 00:10:47.491
but as President of the United States.

223
00:10:47.527 --> 00:10:49.392
your most steadfast ally.

224
00:10:49.428 --> 00:10:52.118
You can believe him there. Jozef.

225
00:10:52.141 --> 00:10:54.197
We can<i> all</i> believe him.

226
00:10:54.233 --> 00:10:57.267
Obviously. I am hoping for your
support at tomorrow's summit.

227
00:10:57.303 --> 00:10:58.569
Thank you.

228
00:10:58.605 --> 00:11:01.705
France looks forward to your proposal.

229
00:11:01.741 --> 00:11:04.374
I appreciate that. Madame.

230
00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:06.510
[Keypad beeps. door opens]

231
00:11:10.082 --> 00:11:12.082
This isn't on the White House tour.

232
00:11:12.113 --> 00:11:16.652
Access to Agent Wells' office
is extremely restricted.

233
00:11:16.688 --> 00:11:18.989
Where<i> is</i> Hannah?

234
00:11:19.025 --> 00:11:21.124
On assignment.

235
00:11:23.562 --> 00:11:25.194
[Keypad beeps]

236
00:11:25.230 --> 00:11:28.230
Any chance we can recover those
deleted Browning Reed files?

237
00:11:28.266 --> 00:11:30.099
Not without a time machine.

238
00:11:30.135 --> 00:11:32.568
Someone ran a brute-force
deletion program.

239
00:11:32.604 --> 00:11:34.269
It's the mother of data erasers.

240
00:11:34.305 --> 00:11:36.238
Cleaned them right off
the White House servers.

241
00:11:36.274 --> 00:11:37.439
So we got nothing.

242
00:11:37.475 --> 00:11:39.140
I didn't say that.

243
00:11:39.143 --> 00:11:41.077
Because there were so
many files to begin with.

244
00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:42.678
whoever's been covering their tracks

245
00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:44.147
has been deleting them in small batches

246
00:11:44.149 --> 00:11:45.723
over the past few months.

247
00:11:45.726 --> 00:11:47.616
There are only five
files still remaining

248
00:11:47.652 --> 00:11:49.451
associated with Browning Reed.

249
00:11:49.487 --> 00:11:51.487
Gonna need you to make
copies and print them up.

250
00:11:51.523 --> 00:11:53.523
Check this out.

251
00:11:54.897 --> 00:11:56.639
It's a digital fingerprint left behind

252
00:11:56.661 --> 00:11:58.159
by the person who deleted the files.

253
00:11:58.195 --> 00:12:00.378
Now. they tend to be
unique. but if I'm good...

254
00:12:00.381 --> 00:12:02.063
And I like to think I am...

255
00:12:02.099 --> 00:12:04.933
I can program a trace and
plant it in the remaining files.

256
00:12:04.969 --> 00:12:07.769
So if the traitor tries
to delete any of them.

257
00:12:07.805 --> 00:12:10.371
we can track the user back
to an exact I.P. address.

258
00:12:10.407 --> 00:12:11.772
Exactly.

259
00:12:11.808 --> 00:12:14.275
How long will it take
you to build a trace?

260
00:12:14.311 --> 00:12:16.344
- A few hours?
- You got<i> one.</i>

261
00:12:17.494 --> 00:12:19.939
Those files are the
only lead to the insider.

262
00:12:19.983 --> 00:12:21.815
and once they're
deleted. we got nothing.

263
00:12:21.851 --> 00:12:23.485
No pressure. huh? [Chuckles]

264
00:12:30.994 --> 00:12:34.327
Well. thank you. Yes.
Thank you very much.

265
00:12:34.363 --> 00:12:36.163
Well. that's it.

266
00:12:36.199 --> 00:12:38.832
Our proposal is the
third item on the agenda.

267
00:12:38.868 --> 00:12:40.000
We're on our way.

268
00:12:40.036 --> 00:12:42.335
- No media. right?
- Nope.

269
00:12:42.371 --> 00:12:45.338
Just you and 27 other
leaders of the free world.

270
00:12:45.374 --> 00:12:47.340
- [Sighs]
- Relax. Tom.

271
00:12:47.376 --> 00:12:49.609
All we're asking is
to start a conversation

272
00:12:49.645 --> 00:12:51.211
that's long overdue.

273
00:12:51.247 --> 00:12:52.845
- [Knock on door]
- Come in.

274
00:12:52.881 --> 00:12:54.514
Seth.

275
00:12:54.550 --> 00:12:57.050
Hey. Sorry to disturb
you. Mr. President.

276
00:12:57.086 --> 00:12:59.292
I just. um. thought you
should see this right away.

277
00:12:59.295 --> 00:13:00.694
[Door closes]

278
00:13:08.030 --> 00:13:09.632
Why didn't we get a heads-up?

279
00:13:09.635 --> 00:13:12.202
We did. Abe asked me about Al-Sakar
a couple days ago. remember?

280
00:13:12.205 --> 00:13:13.836
Right.

281
00:13:13.839 --> 00:13:15.869
We stonewalled. I thought
that was the end of it.

282
00:13:15.871 --> 00:13:17.470
Then he published anyway.

283
00:13:17.506 --> 00:13:18.670
[Scoffs]

284
00:13:18.706 --> 00:13:19.938
Emily: <i>So. what's our plan?</i>

285
00:13:19.974 --> 00:13:21.273
This is total crap!

286
00:13:21.309 --> 00:13:22.708
We're figuring that out right now.

287
00:13:22.744 --> 00:13:24.176
I'll call you back.

288
00:13:24.212 --> 00:13:26.345
I knew Abe Leonard.
He was a good reporter

289
00:13:26.381 --> 00:13:29.515
until he started getting fast
and loose with his sources.

290
00:13:29.551 --> 00:13:31.517
You should have no problem
shooting this one down.

291
00:13:31.553 --> 00:13:34.185
Just tell them it's nothing
but a big pack of lies.

292
00:13:34.221 --> 00:13:36.888
No. I want our position to
be that this is conjecture.

293
00:13:36.924 --> 00:13:40.092
but we will investigate
all of the allegations.

294
00:13:40.128 --> 00:13:42.894
Sorry. sir. Why not just
openly deny it if it's not true?

295
00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:43.751
Seth's right.

296
00:13:43.754 --> 00:13:46.098
Deflecting this now is
only gonna raise suspicion.

297
00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:48.700
Yeah. the American people
believe that we captured

298
00:13:48.736 --> 00:13:50.636
the terrorists responsible
for the Capitol bombing.

299
00:13:50.638 --> 00:13:52.837
This article says that
we got the wrong guy.

300
00:13:52.873 --> 00:13:55.006
I mean. if we don't push back hard now.

301
00:13:55.042 --> 00:13:56.975
confidence in the
administration's gonna tank.

302
00:13:59.913 --> 00:14:01.779
You can say that we're standing by

303
00:14:01.815 --> 00:14:04.482
our intelligence agencies
and our military officials.

304
00:14:04.510 --> 00:14:06.478
I'm sorry. Mr. President. I
don't think that goes far enough.

305
00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:08.485
Just write it up and
bring it back to me!

306
00:14:08.521 --> 00:14:09.987
Yes. sir.

307
00:14:10.023 --> 00:14:13.357
[Door opens. closes]

308
00:14:17.197 --> 00:14:19.130
What the hell was that?

309
00:14:20.100 --> 00:14:21.465
It's how I have to handle this.

310
00:14:24.001 --> 00:14:27.205
You realize this story puts
your credibility at risk.

311
00:14:28.318 --> 00:14:31.074
Your 100 days. everything
we want to do here.

312
00:14:31.110 --> 00:14:33.611
goes right out the window if
you don't crush this right now.

313
00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:36.647
- I can't.
- Why not?

314
00:14:37.983 --> 00:14:39.717
Because it's true.

315
00:14:51.583 --> 00:14:53.483
Unbelievable.

316
00:14:53.485 --> 00:14:54.984
A homegrown conspiracy?

317
00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:57.220
A possible traitor in the White House?

318
00:14:57.256 --> 00:14:59.155
Yeah.

319
00:14:59.191 --> 00:15:00.523
And you didn't tell me?

320
00:15:00.559 --> 00:15:01.890
It was a matter of security.

321
00:15:01.926 --> 00:15:03.659
Emily doesn't know. Neither does Seth.

322
00:15:03.695 --> 00:15:05.995
Well. I'm your Secretary
of State. for God's sake.

323
00:15:06.031 --> 00:15:07.763
I mean. I-I'm in the line of succession.

324
00:15:07.799 --> 00:15:09.264
You didn't think you could trust<i> me?</i>

325
00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:10.967
- This isn't a matter of trust.
- The hell it's not!

326
00:15:10.969 --> 00:15:12.735
Now. I came out of retirement for you.

327
00:15:12.771 --> 00:15:14.503
I put my legacy on the line for you!

328
00:15:14.539 --> 00:15:16.071
And this is how you repay me?!

329
00:15:16.107 --> 00:15:18.107
- I thought I had it handled.
- Well. you were wrong.

330
00:15:18.109 --> 00:15:19.508
You were dead wrong. and now my head

331
00:15:19.510 --> 00:15:21.009
is on the block right along with yours!

332
00:15:21.011 --> 00:15:22.411
Well. I probably should've let you in.

333
00:15:22.413 --> 00:15:24.412
That is the understatement of the year.

334
00:15:24.448 --> 00:15:27.715
I have seen you exercise poor judgment
before. Tom. but this takes the cake!

335
00:15:27.751 --> 00:15:29.311
Cornelius. I'm sorry if I offended you.

336
00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:30.752
It's the last thing I wanted to do.

337
00:15:30.788 --> 00:15:32.308
But the president of the United States

338
00:15:32.323 --> 00:15:33.921
has a responsibility to protect

339
00:15:33.957 --> 00:15:37.625
classified information
and ongoing investigations.

340
00:15:37.661 --> 00:15:40.094
This isn't a matter of trying
to mislead the American people.

341
00:15:40.130 --> 00:15:41.896
This is about trying to protect them.

342
00:15:41.932 --> 00:15:44.465
And you should know that.

343
00:15:44.501 --> 00:15:47.635
Now. I've made a
mistake. and I am sorry.

344
00:15:49.039 --> 00:15:51.005
But right now I need your counsel.

345
00:15:51.041 --> 00:15:52.973
What are my options?

346
00:15:55.378 --> 00:15:59.246
You don't have any. That's the problem.

347
00:15:59.282 --> 00:16:01.782
You can't deny the story
without committing perjury.

348
00:16:01.818 --> 00:16:03.458
and you can't confirm
it without admitting

349
00:16:03.486 --> 00:16:05.580
that you still don't know
who's behind all this.

350
00:16:05.583 --> 00:16:07.821
throwing the whole American
country into a panic.

351
00:16:07.857 --> 00:16:10.090
That's why we need Seth
to buy us some time.

352
00:16:10.126 --> 00:16:11.457
But how much time?

353
00:16:11.493 --> 00:16:13.827
The jackals are at the
door. Mr. President.

354
00:16:13.863 --> 00:16:16.129
I think we're really close
to cracking this thing.

355
00:16:16.165 --> 00:16:17.630
Do you really?

356
00:16:17.666 --> 00:16:20.266
Your lead investigator
is missing. possibly dead.

357
00:16:20.302 --> 00:16:22.368
The man who tried to
kill you is still alive.

358
00:16:22.404 --> 00:16:24.705
And the mole in the White
House remains unknown.

359
00:16:26.404 --> 00:16:28.174
It looks to me like you're doubling down

360
00:16:28.176 --> 00:16:29.676
on a mighty poor hand.

361
00:16:29.712 --> 00:16:32.846
Well. it's the only hand I was given.

362
00:16:34.717 --> 00:16:37.350
All right.

363
00:16:37.386 --> 00:16:38.719
We brass it out.

364
00:16:40.589 --> 00:16:43.089
[Cellphone rings]

365
00:16:45.026 --> 00:16:46.959
This is Moss.

366
00:16:46.995 --> 00:16:49.195
Yes.

367
00:16:49.231 --> 00:16:52.531
Of course. We'll be right there.

368
00:16:53.655 --> 00:16:56.435
Our allies have requested
our presence downstairs.

369
00:16:58.973 --> 00:17:01.206
They want an explanation for the story.

370
00:17:05.397 --> 00:17:07.530
Morning show host: <i>Welcome back.</i>

371
00:17:07.533 --> 00:17:09.181
<i>We're joined now by
Pulitzer Prize-winning</i>

372
00:17:09.183 --> 00:17:11.283
<i>journalist Abe Leonard. whose story</i>

373
00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:14.185
<i>in today's</i> New York Standard
<i>has raised serious questions</i>

374
00:17:14.221 --> 00:17:16.320
<i>about who was really responsible</i>

375
00:17:16.356 --> 00:17:17.860
<i>for the attack on our Capitol.</i>

376
00:17:17.863 --> 00:17:19.858
<i>- Welcome. Abe.
- Thank you. It's good to be here.</i>

377
00:17:19.860 --> 00:17:21.325
<i>Let's start with the big headline.</i>

378
00:17:21.361 --> 00:17:23.728
<i>Al-Sakar did</i> not <i>blow up the Capitol?</i>

379
00:17:23.764 --> 00:17:26.831
<i>No. They didn't have the
money or the manpower.</i>

380
00:17:26.867 --> 00:17:30.834
<i>Their leader. Majid Nassar.
was paid to take credit.</i>

381
00:17:30.870 --> 00:17:32.737
<i>Paid? By whom?</i>

382
00:17:32.773 --> 00:17:34.372
<i>Nestor Lozano. the man</i>

383
00:17:34.408 --> 00:17:36.540
<i>who tried to assassinate
President Kirkman.</i>

384
00:17:36.576 --> 00:17:38.909
<i>Yet our government went
after Majid Nassar...</i>

385
00:17:38.945 --> 00:17:41.011
<i>Actually captured him
in a S.E.A.L. team raid</i>

386
00:17:41.047 --> 00:17:42.713
<i>where the commanding officer was killed.</i>

387
00:17:42.749 --> 00:17:44.682
<i>I believe they were misled.</i>

388
00:17:44.718 --> 00:17:46.584
<i>Misled by whom?</i>

389
00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:48.118
<i>Bad intelligence.</i>

390
00:17:48.154 --> 00:17:50.254
<i>They bought the story
Lozano was selling.</i>

391
00:17:50.290 --> 00:17:51.588
<i>But who was he protecting?</i>

392
00:17:51.624 --> 00:17:54.357
[Ringing]

393
00:17:54.393 --> 00:17:56.160
[Cellphone rings]

394
00:17:58.085 --> 00:17:59.462
Whitaker.

395
00:17:59.498 --> 00:18:01.398
Are you watching Abe
Leonard on television?

396
00:18:01.434 --> 00:18:04.201
No. but I read his story.

397
00:18:05.705 --> 00:18:07.203
It's all working.

398
00:18:07.239 --> 00:18:10.507
Everyone's focused on the FBI. not us.

399
00:18:10.543 --> 00:18:13.743
Well. that's great. but where did
he get this stuff about Lozano?

400
00:18:13.779 --> 00:18:16.413
I don't know. He did that on his own.

401
00:18:16.449 --> 00:18:18.281
Well. he's treading on dangerous ground.

402
00:18:18.317 --> 00:18:21.151
Not really. He thinks Lozano's
dead. just like everyone else.

403
00:18:25.991 --> 00:18:27.790
Abe Leonard has served his purpose.

404
00:18:29.294 --> 00:18:31.328
Roger that.

405
00:18:33.966 --> 00:18:35.464
Seth: As I said. the president stands

406
00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:37.966
by our intelligence
community and our military.

407
00:18:38.002 --> 00:18:40.169
Answer the question. Seth. Did
Al-Sakar blow up the Capitol?

408
00:18:40.171 --> 00:18:42.137
That is the official
explanation at this time.

409
00:18:42.173 --> 00:18:43.327
But it could change?

410
00:18:43.330 --> 00:18:45.475
All I said is we're looking
into the allegations.

411
00:18:45.477 --> 00:18:47.443
Joel Estevez: So does
that mean you don't know?

412
00:18:47.479 --> 00:18:48.777
It means we're looking into it.

413
00:18:48.813 --> 00:18:50.479
- Seth!
- Yes.

414
00:18:50.515 --> 00:18:52.315
<i>¿El presidente Kirkman
está diciendo la verdad</i>

415
00:18:52.350 --> 00:18:53.481
<i>a la cumbre De la OTAN?</i>

416
00:18:53.517 --> 00:18:55.150
Ah. see? A question about NATO.

417
00:18:55.186 --> 00:18:56.685
Unfortunately. my Spanish
is no longer as good.

418
00:18:56.687 --> 00:18:57.719
Could you repeat the question?

419
00:18:57.721 --> 00:18:58.481
<i>Perdon.</i>

420
00:18:58.484 --> 00:19:01.056
Is President Kirkman telling
the NATO summit the truth?

421
00:19:01.058 --> 00:19:02.757
I've already answered this question.

422
00:19:02.793 --> 00:19:04.726
Of course he's telling the truth.

423
00:19:04.762 --> 00:19:07.595
Joel Estevez: <i>If the president
stands by his intelligence.</i>

424
00:19:07.631 --> 00:19:09.630
<i>why is he looking into the allegations?</i>

425
00:19:09.666 --> 00:19:11.466
<i>Sure. So. I've tried to be perfectly clear.</i>

426
00:19:11.502 --> 00:19:14.134
<i>You want answers. The
president wants answers.</i>

427
00:19:14.170 --> 00:19:16.904
<i>Which is why he is looking
into the allegations. okay?</i>

428
00:19:16.940 --> 00:19:18.339
<i>And he'll make a statement</i>

429
00:19:18.375 --> 00:19:20.074
<i>to the public at the appropriate time.</i>

430
00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:22.577
<i>but right now he is focused
on the first NATO summit.</i>

431
00:19:22.613 --> 00:19:24.693
<i>which is what I would love
to answer questions about.</i>

432
00:19:26.682 --> 00:19:28.649
[Sighs]

433
00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:32.186
[Cellphone rings]

434
00:19:32.222 --> 00:19:34.021
This is Foerstel.

435
00:19:34.057 --> 00:19:35.522
Special Agent Foerstel.

436
00:19:35.558 --> 00:19:37.624
this is Chief Petty
Officer Lucy Fernandez.

437
00:19:37.660 --> 00:19:40.160
U.S. Coast Guard.
Indian River. Delaware.

438
00:19:40.196 --> 00:19:43.497
We received a mayday call
from Hannah Wells last night.

439
00:19:43.533 --> 00:19:45.898
- You found her?
- <i>Not exactly. sir.</i>

440
00:19:45.934 --> 00:19:47.774
Uh. because of the static
of the distress call.

441
00:19:47.802 --> 00:19:49.435
we thought that Hannah Wells was a ship.

442
00:19:49.471 --> 00:19:51.703
It wasn't until we ran the
call through a digital filter

443
00:19:51.739 --> 00:19:54.740
that we realized she was
saying "FBI Agent Hannah Wells."

444
00:19:54.776 --> 00:19:56.875
Okay. I don't understand.

445
00:19:56.911 --> 00:19:59.412
- Do you have her or not?
- We don't.

446
00:19:59.448 --> 00:20:01.947
<i>In response to the mayday. we
scrambled an H-65 helicopter</i>

447
00:20:01.983 --> 00:20:03.543
and a response boat to the coordinates.

448
00:20:03.551 --> 00:20:04.883
but the results were negative.

449
00:20:04.919 --> 00:20:06.284
Okay. So where does this leave us?

450
00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:08.080
Uh. we're working on a
broadened search grid.

451
00:20:08.089 --> 00:20:11.056
factoring in current changes.
but it's gonna take time.

452
00:20:11.092 --> 00:20:13.024
All right. I'm gonna be
there within the hour.

453
00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:15.126
I'm gonna want better answers than that.

454
00:20:15.162 --> 00:20:18.096
♪ ♪

455
00:20:18.132 --> 00:20:20.165
[Door opens]

456
00:20:40.353 --> 00:20:43.054
Peter MacLeish was a brother to me.

457
00:20:44.725 --> 00:20:46.858
You kill my family...

458
00:20:48.729 --> 00:20:50.495
I kill yours.

459
00:20:52.598 --> 00:20:54.198
[Ring clanks]

460
00:21:11.216 --> 00:21:13.316
Jason...

461
00:21:13.352 --> 00:21:16.119
♪ ♪

462
00:21:28.667 --> 00:21:30.647
[Indistinct conversations]

463
00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:32.222
Good morning.

464
00:21:32.253 --> 00:21:34.877
I know that there has been
a great deal of speculation

465
00:21:34.913 --> 00:21:36.778
with regards to an
article that was published

466
00:21:36.814 --> 00:21:39.014
in this morning's <i>New York Standard.</i>

467
00:21:39.050 --> 00:21:42.083
Although I cannot confirm
or deny the allegations.

468
00:21:42.119 --> 00:21:45.286
I can tell you in
confidence that my government

469
00:21:45.322 --> 00:21:47.923
is in the middle of an
extensive investigation

470
00:21:47.959 --> 00:21:50.125
that is highly classified.

471
00:21:50.161 --> 00:21:52.560
Unfortunately at this time. I
cannot share that information

472
00:21:52.596 --> 00:21:54.629
with you because of reasons
of national security.

473
00:21:54.665 --> 00:21:56.797
Mr. President. you can be assured

474
00:21:56.833 --> 00:21:58.166
of our continued support.

475
00:21:58.202 --> 00:21:59.567
Thank you. Chancellor.

476
00:21:59.603 --> 00:22:01.769
Then. in the spirit of
mutual understanding.

477
00:22:01.805 --> 00:22:03.771
I suggest that we move
over to the initiative

478
00:22:03.807 --> 00:22:05.105
regarding nuclear disarmament.

479
00:22:05.141 --> 00:22:07.008
I'm sorry. Mr. President.

480
00:22:07.044 --> 00:22:09.744
But France is not satisfied.

481
00:22:11.314 --> 00:22:13.948
May I remind the new American president

482
00:22:13.984 --> 00:22:16.417
that when he initiated a mission

483
00:22:16.453 --> 00:22:19.253
to capture Majid Nassar in Algeria.

484
00:22:19.289 --> 00:22:22.222
we allowed him to use French airspace.

485
00:22:22.258 --> 00:22:25.125
Spanish radar assets
and Italian naval support

486
00:22:25.161 --> 00:22:27.227
were also employed.

487
00:22:27.263 --> 00:22:30.464
Now. we must all face the
fact that we supported you

488
00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:33.487
under what might turn
into false pretenses.

489
00:22:33.490 --> 00:22:34.990
We deserve to know

490
00:22:34.993 --> 00:22:39.761
if Al-Sakar did not
perpetrate the Capitol bombing.

491
00:22:39.789 --> 00:22:42.188
I'm afraid my government
agrees. Mr. President.

492
00:22:42.229 --> 00:22:44.143
We have learned from
our mistakes in Iraq.

493
00:22:44.179 --> 00:22:45.979
We cannot discuss your
initiative any further

494
00:22:46.015 --> 00:22:47.346
without knowing the truth.

495
00:22:47.382 --> 00:22:49.783
If my esteemed
colleagues will excuse me.

496
00:22:49.819 --> 00:22:53.286
you are not seriously suggesting
that the French and British

497
00:22:53.322 --> 00:22:55.654
don't have classified intelligence

498
00:22:55.690 --> 00:22:58.924
that they keep secret for
reasons of national security.

499
00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:00.793
<i>Mais oui.</i>

500
00:23:00.829 --> 00:23:05.044
Of course we have our
discretions. Secretary Moss.

501
00:23:05.047 --> 00:23:08.334
But we also have reason
to trust each other.

502
00:23:08.370 --> 00:23:12.104
a long history of
cooperation and experience.

503
00:23:12.140 --> 00:23:15.407
Monsieur Kirkman has no such history.

504
00:23:15.443 --> 00:23:18.110
He is president only because

505
00:23:18.146 --> 00:23:20.646
the previous government was wiped out.

506
00:23:20.682 --> 00:23:22.181
[Murmuring]

507
00:23:23.685 --> 00:23:26.251
No. my point is...

508
00:23:26.287 --> 00:23:30.155
how can we trust someone
who appears to be a...

509
00:23:30.191 --> 00:23:32.190
What's the word?

510
00:23:32.226 --> 00:23:34.692
<i>Gaffeur. Maladroit.</i>

511
00:23:34.728 --> 00:23:37.763
I believe the word you're
searching for is "blunderer."

512
00:23:39.733 --> 00:23:41.333
<i>Oui.</i>

513
00:23:41.369 --> 00:23:46.403
Who apparently abused article
five of the NATO charter

514
00:23:46.439 --> 00:23:51.276
by asking us to assist him in
going after the wrong target.

515
00:23:52.579 --> 00:23:56.080
As I said earlier.
Madame. I am not at liberty

516
00:23:56.116 --> 00:23:58.816
to comment on that any
further than I already have.

517
00:23:58.852 --> 00:24:01.902
Then France proposes
tabling any discussion

518
00:24:01.905 --> 00:24:03.470
of the U.S. initiative

519
00:24:03.473 --> 00:24:07.642
until the president
<i>can</i> say more and does.

520
00:24:10.598 --> 00:24:13.531
All I can do...

521
00:24:13.567 --> 00:24:18.035
is ask you all. please...

522
00:24:18.071 --> 00:24:21.972
please do not allow my
nation's domestic issues

523
00:24:22.008 --> 00:24:24.875
to interfere with our global objectives.

524
00:24:24.911 --> 00:24:26.843
Then I move to have the
Nuclear Planning Group

525
00:24:26.879 --> 00:24:28.879
revisit the initiative this afternoon.

526
00:24:28.915 --> 00:24:30.714
The Nuclear Planning Group

527
00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:34.050
will meet after the morning
session to... reconsider.

528
00:24:34.086 --> 00:24:35.418
Thank you.

529
00:24:35.454 --> 00:24:36.819
[Clears throat]

530
00:24:36.855 --> 00:24:39.021
Now let's move to some of the less...

531
00:24:39.057 --> 00:24:41.791
controversial items on our agenda.

532
00:24:44.129 --> 00:24:46.362
[Keys clacking]

533
00:24:46.398 --> 00:24:49.732
The trace has been planted.

534
00:24:49.768 --> 00:24:51.600
If someone deletes these digital files.

535
00:24:51.636 --> 00:24:54.303
we'll be able to track the bastard.

536
00:24:56.141 --> 00:24:59.041
Don't thank me all at once.

537
00:24:59.077 --> 00:25:01.315
[Cheers and applause]

538
00:25:01.318 --> 00:25:03.046
- Abe: All right. all right.
- Man: Way to go. Abe!

539
00:25:03.048 --> 00:25:04.546
Thank you. Thank you very much.

540
00:25:04.582 --> 00:25:07.749
Thank you. Go back to work. Enough.

541
00:25:07.785 --> 00:25:09.984
All right. thank you.

542
00:25:10.020 --> 00:25:12.053
[Sighs] All right. Thank you very much.

543
00:25:12.089 --> 00:25:13.389
- Good job. Great job.
- Thank you.

544
00:25:13.391 --> 00:25:14.856
You didn't get my texts?

545
00:25:14.892 --> 00:25:17.259
Well. I've been busy making us famous.

546
00:25:17.295 --> 00:25:18.793
Come in.

547
00:25:18.829 --> 00:25:22.264
Abe Leonard. Alyssa Abboud.

548
00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:25.100
Uh. are we here to discuss
promotional opportunities?

549
00:25:25.136 --> 00:25:27.301
Actually. Alyssa's from Legal.

550
00:25:27.337 --> 00:25:28.607
Oh.

551
00:25:28.610 --> 00:25:30.772
The FBI wants to talk to you.

552
00:25:30.808 --> 00:25:33.475
[Laughs]

553
00:25:34.611 --> 00:25:36.277
That's so predictable.

554
00:25:36.313 --> 00:25:38.379
I just didn't expect it this soon.

555
00:25:38.415 --> 00:25:39.315
Abe...

556
00:25:39.318 --> 00:25:40.895
For weeks. I couldn't
get them on the phone.

557
00:25:40.897 --> 00:25:42.983
They even put a tail on
me to try and scare me off.

558
00:25:42.986 --> 00:25:44.752
What? <i>Now</i> they want to talk?

559
00:25:44.788 --> 00:25:46.854
I mean. forget it. I'm
not talking to them.

560
00:25:46.890 --> 00:25:48.322
We'd like you to.

561
00:25:48.358 --> 00:25:49.626
I'm sorry. What?

562
00:25:49.629 --> 00:25:51.559
They believe that you
could be a potential witness

563
00:25:51.561 --> 00:25:53.395
in their investigation
into the Capitol bombing.

564
00:25:53.397 --> 00:25:55.996
No way. I'm not giving up my sources!

565
00:25:56.032 --> 00:25:57.264
No one's asking you to.

566
00:25:57.300 --> 00:25:58.932
So what are you asking me?

567
00:25:58.968 --> 00:26:00.934
To go in for an interview. That's all.

568
00:26:00.970 --> 00:26:02.769
- See what they want.
- Why should I?

569
00:26:02.805 --> 00:26:04.471
Because they can
subpoena you if you don't.

570
00:26:04.473 --> 00:26:05.624
Fine. Let 'em.

571
00:26:05.627 --> 00:26:07.974
What Alyssa's saying is
if you go in voluntarily.

572
00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:10.277
it buys good will. for
you and the paper...

573
00:26:10.313 --> 00:26:11.978
The paper that gave
you the time and money

574
00:26:12.014 --> 00:26:13.313
and support to get this story.

575
00:26:13.349 --> 00:26:14.648
Yeah. and possibly pick up

576
00:26:14.684 --> 00:26:16.309
another Pulitzer for their troubles.

577
00:26:19.054 --> 00:26:20.953
I'm asking you. Abe.

578
00:26:20.989 --> 00:26:24.157
This is what New York wants.

579
00:26:24.193 --> 00:26:25.725
It's important to me.

580
00:26:31.033 --> 00:26:33.133
[Sighs]

581
00:26:35.136 --> 00:26:36.202
Okay.

582
00:26:37.539 --> 00:26:39.004
Well. I guess it's a date.

583
00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:42.241
We'll leave together
from here. One hour.

584
00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:47.979
What's her problem?

585
00:26:48.015 --> 00:26:49.848
She represents journalists.

586
00:26:49.884 --> 00:26:51.884
[Laughs]

587
00:26:53.621 --> 00:26:55.820
Hey. You never told me
about<i> Air Force One.</i>

588
00:26:55.823 --> 00:26:58.690
I can't believe you're asking
me about that on a day like this.

589
00:26:58.726 --> 00:27:00.025
I want to know how it went.

590
00:27:00.061 --> 00:27:01.659
I'm really crazy-busy right now. Emily.

591
00:27:01.695 --> 00:27:03.929
Everyone is crazy-busy right now. Seth.

592
00:27:03.965 --> 00:27:05.197
Really quickly. just tell me.

593
00:27:05.233 --> 00:27:06.741
was it everything you'd hoped it'd be?

594
00:27:06.743 --> 00:27:08.999
Uh. let's just say that the anticipation

595
00:27:09.035 --> 00:27:10.835
far outweighed the actual event.

596
00:27:10.871 --> 00:27:12.871
Mm. So I heard.

597
00:27:15.909 --> 00:27:18.343
What do you mean? Moss told you?

598
00:27:18.379 --> 00:27:20.311
He may have sent me a photo.

599
00:27:21.915 --> 00:27:25.015
We are no longer friends.

600
00:27:25.051 --> 00:27:26.751
[Laughs]

601
00:27:30.988 --> 00:27:33.955
Fernandez? Agent Foerstel.

602
00:27:33.958 --> 00:27:35.926
- Nice to meet you.
- Status update.

603
00:27:35.962 --> 00:27:38.829
We've covered this entire
area. So far. nothing.

604
00:27:38.865 --> 00:27:40.270
It's unacceptable.

605
00:27:40.273 --> 00:27:42.399
The ship must have
disabled its transponder.

606
00:27:42.435 --> 00:27:44.067
You add in rough seas and a low ceiling.

607
00:27:44.103 --> 00:27:45.702
it makes the search twice as difficult.

608
00:27:45.738 --> 00:27:48.071
I need you to put every
resource you have on this.

609
00:27:48.107 --> 00:27:49.573
It's already being done. sir.

610
00:27:49.609 --> 00:27:51.508
But. in my experience.

611
00:27:51.544 --> 00:27:53.744
it's hard to find a ship
that doesn't want to be found.

612
00:27:53.780 --> 00:27:56.246
I don't care. Find it.

613
00:28:03.373 --> 00:28:05.739
- [Knock on door]
- Come in.

614
00:28:05.775 --> 00:28:08.174
It's the readout we drafted
for the afternoon session...

615
00:28:08.210 --> 00:28:09.576
Minus the U.S. initiative.

616
00:28:09.612 --> 00:28:11.411
It's just standard boilerplate.

617
00:28:11.447 --> 00:28:15.048
If you're good with it.
I'll get it out to the pool.

618
00:28:15.084 --> 00:28:16.783
This is fine. Send it out.

619
00:28:16.819 --> 00:28:18.819
- Thank you.
- Seth...

620
00:28:21.156 --> 00:28:22.856
Thank you for what
you did this afternoon.

621
00:28:22.892 --> 00:28:24.858
Oh. you mean dying on the world stage?

622
00:28:24.894 --> 00:28:26.842
[Chuckles] Yeah.

623
00:28:29.131 --> 00:28:30.596
Pretty awful. wasn't it?

624
00:28:30.632 --> 00:28:32.131
Well. look. I'll be honest.

625
00:28:32.167 --> 00:28:35.301
It was one of my more
colorful briefings.

626
00:28:35.337 --> 00:28:38.004
But your job is way harder
than mine. especially right now.

627
00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:40.773
I appreciate you saying that.

628
00:28:40.809 --> 00:28:43.308
And I appreciate you not
asking for more information.

629
00:28:43.344 --> 00:28:45.143
Well. I've known you
for a while now. sir.

630
00:28:45.179 --> 00:28:47.813
Long enough to know that.
uh. when you make a decision.

631
00:28:47.849 --> 00:28:50.249
it's for a good reason. and
that's good enough for me.

632
00:28:50.285 --> 00:28:52.284
Just wish it was good
enough for the press.

633
00:28:52.320 --> 00:28:53.285
Yeah.

634
00:28:53.324 --> 00:28:56.755
Excuse me. This might be important.

635
00:28:56.791 --> 00:28:58.723
Seth Wright.

636
00:28:58.759 --> 00:29:00.559
Thank you.

637
00:29:02.524 --> 00:29:04.523
The Nuclear Planning Group voted.

638
00:29:04.526 --> 00:29:07.456
They're not gonna be putting your
initiative back on the agenda.

639
00:29:07.459 --> 00:29:08.867
So that's it then.

640
00:29:10.342 --> 00:29:11.936
[Knock on door. door opens]

641
00:29:11.972 --> 00:29:14.138
Sir. the First Lady's
on the phone for you.

642
00:29:14.174 --> 00:29:16.474
- Thank you.
- [Door closes]

643
00:29:16.510 --> 00:29:17.742
I'm sorry. sir.

644
00:29:17.778 --> 00:29:19.478
Next time.

645
00:29:26.687 --> 00:29:27.652
Alex.

646
00:29:27.688 --> 00:29:29.287
Hey.

647
00:29:29.323 --> 00:29:30.788
<i>Everything all right?</i>

648
00:29:30.824 --> 00:29:33.791
We're fine. How are<i> you?</i>

649
00:29:33.827 --> 00:29:36.827
I've been better.

650
00:29:36.863 --> 00:29:38.862
[Sighs] I'm sorry.

651
00:29:38.898 --> 00:29:41.433
I know this can't be easy.

652
00:29:42.402 --> 00:29:44.035
No.

653
00:29:44.071 --> 00:29:45.937
[Sighs]

654
00:29:48.207 --> 00:29:51.875
So. I've... I've been
thinking about you all day.

655
00:29:51.911 --> 00:29:53.844
You know. the story.

656
00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:56.547
I-I think I understand.

657
00:29:56.583 --> 00:29:58.816
Understand what?

658
00:29:58.852 --> 00:30:01.717
You shutting me out at the hospital

659
00:30:01.753 --> 00:30:03.886
when that FBI agent came to see you...

660
00:30:03.922 --> 00:30:08.858
the way you react every
time Mike enters a room...

661
00:30:08.894 --> 00:30:11.527
the reason you can't let the family

662
00:30:11.563 --> 00:30:13.696
<i>come back to the White House.</i>

663
00:30:13.732 --> 00:30:15.765
It's true. isn't it?

664
00:30:15.801 --> 00:30:17.367
Someone else blew up the Capitol.

665
00:30:17.403 --> 00:30:20.770
and you don't know who it is. do you?

666
00:30:20.806 --> 00:30:21.905
Tom?

667
00:30:23.141 --> 00:30:26.208
There are so many things
I've wanted to tell you.

668
00:30:26.244 --> 00:30:28.277
<i>So many things I still want to tell you.</i>

669
00:30:28.313 --> 00:30:30.112
But you can't.

670
00:30:30.148 --> 00:30:32.414
[Chuckles softly]

671
00:30:32.450 --> 00:30:34.616
I was thinking.

672
00:30:34.652 --> 00:30:37.386
a year ago...

673
00:30:37.422 --> 00:30:39.888
the only thing I ever had
to worry about on a weekday

674
00:30:39.924 --> 00:30:42.824
was whether or not I'd get to
Penny's soccer practice on time.

675
00:30:42.860 --> 00:30:45.427
That is a lifetime ago.

676
00:30:45.463 --> 00:30:47.497
Yeah.

677
00:30:49.967 --> 00:30:53.969
Tom. how can I help you?

678
00:30:57.274 --> 00:30:59.107
Don't lose faith in me.

679
00:30:59.143 --> 00:31:01.943
Come on.

680
00:31:01.979 --> 00:31:04.446
I'm always on your side. right?

681
00:31:08.985 --> 00:31:11.285
Fernandez: Okay? Got it. Thanks.

682
00:31:11.321 --> 00:31:12.887
I think we found 'em.

683
00:31:12.923 --> 00:31:14.055
Where?

684
00:31:14.091 --> 00:31:15.623
Port of Baltimore.

685
00:31:15.659 --> 00:31:17.858
They just received a call
from an unscheduled freighter

686
00:31:17.894 --> 00:31:19.927
looking to unload cargo.
Location works out.

687
00:31:19.963 --> 00:31:21.195
When it's estimated to arrive?

688
00:31:21.231 --> 00:31:22.863
Less than an hour. Slip 216.

689
00:31:22.899 --> 00:31:24.598
Yes. Foerstel.

690
00:31:24.634 --> 00:31:27.835
I need an HRT en route to the
Port of Baltimore. Slip 216.

691
00:31:27.871 --> 00:31:29.070
I'm gonna meet them there.

692
00:31:31.340 --> 00:31:34.875
Mr. Leonard. thank you for coming in.

693
00:31:34.911 --> 00:31:36.376
My pleasure.

694
00:31:36.412 --> 00:31:37.845
Should we get started?

695
00:31:37.881 --> 00:31:40.081
Do I have to answer that?

696
00:31:42.585 --> 00:31:44.518
♪ ♪

697
00:31:44.554 --> 00:31:46.186
You don't agree.

698
00:31:46.222 --> 00:31:47.687
That's not what I'm saying.

699
00:31:47.723 --> 00:31:49.389
But you don't think it'll work.

700
00:31:49.425 --> 00:31:51.058
What I think doesn't matter right now.

701
00:31:51.094 --> 00:31:52.392
It's what the president thinks.

702
00:31:52.428 --> 00:31:55.962
And I support the president.

703
00:31:55.998 --> 00:31:57.263
Now. Prime Minister Massett

704
00:31:57.299 --> 00:31:59.331
has agreed to give you five minutes.

705
00:31:59.367 --> 00:32:01.234
So...

706
00:32:02.504 --> 00:32:04.838
Make 'em count.

707
00:32:05.874 --> 00:32:08.075
See you in five minutes.

708
00:32:09.211 --> 00:32:11.477
Thank you.

709
00:32:11.513 --> 00:32:13.213
Thank you. Madame. for seeing me.

710
00:32:14.882 --> 00:32:19.184
You understand why we took the
initiative off of the agenda.

711
00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:23.889
I did not agree with it.
but. yes. I understand.

712
00:32:23.925 --> 00:32:25.223
I need to earn your trust.

713
00:32:25.259 --> 00:32:28.393
Oh. not just me. All of NATO.

714
00:32:28.429 --> 00:32:30.495
[Chuckles] Fine.

715
00:32:30.531 --> 00:32:32.397
But I would like to start with France.

716
00:32:32.433 --> 00:32:35.233
We began this dream of
weapons reduction together.

717
00:32:35.269 --> 00:32:37.535
And I will need you there to finish it.

718
00:32:37.571 --> 00:32:40.438
And how do you expect to do that?

719
00:32:40.474 --> 00:32:42.873
By proving to you that the
United States is serious

720
00:32:42.909 --> 00:32:44.588
about reducing the nuclear threat.

721
00:32:46.713 --> 00:32:48.413
My country has 200 missiles

722
00:32:48.449 --> 00:32:50.448
in bunkers scattered across Europe.

723
00:32:50.484 --> 00:32:52.349
Russia has twice that number.

724
00:32:52.385 --> 00:32:54.785
The old dogmas of mutually
assured destruction

725
00:32:54.821 --> 00:32:57.054
versus secondary strike capabilities

726
00:32:57.090 --> 00:32:59.156
need to be seriously re-examined.

727
00:32:59.192 --> 00:33:00.524
especially given the threat

728
00:33:00.560 --> 00:33:02.000
of our control systems being hacked.

729
00:33:02.029 --> 00:33:03.575
It's a terrifying thought.

730
00:33:03.578 --> 00:33:04.876
Yes. it is.

731
00:33:04.879 --> 00:33:06.597
And the more weapons that are out there.

732
00:33:06.599 --> 00:33:08.999
the greater chance
something could go wrong.

733
00:33:09.035 --> 00:33:11.401
For me. it is very simple.

734
00:33:11.437 --> 00:33:14.738
What kind of a world do we
want to leave our children?

735
00:33:20.613 --> 00:33:22.613
You are a dreamer. sir.

736
00:33:22.649 --> 00:33:24.581
[Chuckles] Yes.

737
00:33:24.617 --> 00:33:26.616
Yes. I am.

738
00:33:26.652 --> 00:33:28.485
And I won't apologize for that.

739
00:33:30.224 --> 00:33:32.288
I have asked Secretary Moss to begin

740
00:33:32.324 --> 00:33:34.124
bilateral negotiations with Russia

741
00:33:34.160 --> 00:33:37.961
in the hopes that you will join us soon.

742
00:33:37.997 --> 00:33:40.068
Madame...

743
00:33:40.071 --> 00:33:42.651
I do hope you join us.

744
00:33:42.654 --> 00:33:45.355
Because I believe wherever
France goes. NATO will follow.

745
00:33:49.441 --> 00:33:54.010
I hope we can discuss this
more fully at the next summit.

746
00:33:58.750 --> 00:34:01.117
I would like nothing more.

747
00:34:04.322 --> 00:34:07.456
[Indistinct conversations in distance]

748
00:34:15.833 --> 00:34:17.965
[<i>Video-game music plays</i>]

749
00:34:18.001 --> 00:34:20.468
[<i>Weapon zapping</i>]

750
00:34:20.504 --> 00:34:22.838
[Rapid beeping]

751
00:34:29.847 --> 00:34:32.113
[Ringing]

752
00:34:32.149 --> 00:34:33.314
Ritter:<i> Ritter.</i>

753
00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:35.416
We got the son of a bitch.

754
00:34:35.452 --> 00:34:37.052
Where is he?

755
00:34:40.518 --> 00:34:41.823
The West Wing.

756
00:34:43.861 --> 00:34:45.360
[Indistinct conversations]

757
00:34:51.868 --> 00:34:54.901
[Indistinct conversations]

758
00:34:54.937 --> 00:34:57.571
Okay. our guy's on the move.
Go straight and take a right.

759
00:34:57.607 --> 00:34:59.473
[Telephone rings]

760
00:34:59.509 --> 00:35:00.774
<i>Yeah. Keep going.</i>

761
00:35:00.811 --> 00:35:01.811
How much farther?

762
00:35:01.814 --> 00:35:03.759
<i>Take a left at the end of the hallway.</i>

763
00:35:04.781 --> 00:35:07.147
Wait. wait. wait. wait.
wait. Actually take a right.

764
00:35:07.183 --> 00:35:09.149
<i>Um...</i>

765
00:35:09.185 --> 00:35:12.018
No. Wait.

766
00:35:12.054 --> 00:35:13.620
Where am I going. Chuck?

767
00:35:13.656 --> 00:35:15.488
<i>No. no. no. no. Come on. Come on.</i>

768
00:35:15.524 --> 00:35:16.657
What happened?

769
00:35:21.730 --> 00:35:23.696
Our guy.

770
00:35:23.732 --> 00:35:25.732
[Beeping]

771
00:35:25.768 --> 00:35:27.768
He cloned his digital fingerprint.

772
00:35:28.415 --> 00:35:30.337
_

773
00:35:36.495 --> 00:35:38.694
[Sighs]

774
00:35:55.646 --> 00:35:56.778
[Whispers] Hey.

775
00:35:56.814 --> 00:35:58.546
Hey.

776
00:35:58.582 --> 00:36:00.414
Poor guy.

777
00:36:00.450 --> 00:36:02.450
Not quite the trip he expected.

778
00:36:02.486 --> 00:36:04.452
Not quite the trip <i>anyone</i> expected.

779
00:36:04.488 --> 00:36:05.987
True enough.

780
00:36:06.023 --> 00:36:07.789
Thank you.

781
00:36:07.825 --> 00:36:08.957
What for?

782
00:36:08.993 --> 00:36:10.057
For standing by me.

783
00:36:10.093 --> 00:36:11.825
Well...

784
00:36:11.861 --> 00:36:13.660
you didn't give me much choice.

785
00:36:13.696 --> 00:36:15.863
If you go down. I go down with you.

786
00:36:15.899 --> 00:36:16.998
I'm being serious.

787
00:36:17.034 --> 00:36:19.300
Well. I am. too.

788
00:36:19.336 --> 00:36:21.502
You know. you drive me nuts. Tom.

789
00:36:21.545 --> 00:36:24.178
You're just so damn...
academic at times.

790
00:36:24.207 --> 00:36:26.074
I want to slap you upside the head.

791
00:36:28.210 --> 00:36:31.879
But damn if I don't see
something special in you.

792
00:36:31.915 --> 00:36:34.515
something that might...

793
00:36:34.551 --> 00:36:36.350
Well. might even approach greatness...

794
00:36:38.555 --> 00:36:40.286
if you don't trip over your own feet.

795
00:36:40.322 --> 00:36:43.724
Thank you. I think.

796
00:36:45.094 --> 00:36:48.728
But we're not out of the
woods yet. Not by a long shot.

797
00:36:48.764 --> 00:36:50.696
You may have salvaged some credibility

798
00:36:50.732 --> 00:36:52.065
with NATO for the time being.

799
00:36:52.101 --> 00:36:54.834
but we're gonna have
a whole new firestorm

800
00:36:54.870 --> 00:36:56.503
waiting for us when we land.

801
00:36:56.539 --> 00:36:57.937
I know.

802
00:36:57.973 --> 00:36:59.706
You ready for it?

803
00:37:01.810 --> 00:37:03.209
I'm gonna have to be.

804
00:37:09.017 --> 00:37:11.551
[Door closes]

805
00:37:11.587 --> 00:37:13.986
Anchor: <i>President Kirkman
returns this afternoon</i>

806
00:37:14.022 --> 00:37:15.955
<i>to a very different political landscape</i>

807
00:37:15.991 --> 00:37:18.190
<i>than the one he left just yesterday.</i>

808
00:37:18.226 --> 00:37:20.059
<i>Abe Leonard's bombshell story.</i>

809
00:37:20.095 --> 00:37:22.361
<i>which asserts Al-Sakar
was not responsible</i>

810
00:37:22.397 --> 00:37:24.196
<i>for the attack at the Capitol.</i>

811
00:37:24.232 --> 00:37:26.098
<i>sent shock waves through Washington.</i>

812
00:37:26.134 --> 00:37:28.700
<i>and it couldn't have come at a
worse time for the president.</i>

813
00:37:28.736 --> 00:37:31.570
<i>who's at the height of his
first international trip.</i>

814
00:37:31.606 --> 00:37:33.738
<i>Many are calling this the worst day</i>

815
00:37:33.774 --> 00:37:35.440
<i>of Kirkman's young presidency.</i>

816
00:37:35.476 --> 00:37:37.576
[Sirens wailing]

817
00:37:43.250 --> 00:37:45.618
[Tires screech]

818
00:37:52.626 --> 00:37:54.292
Man: Let's go! Let's go!

819
00:37:54.328 --> 00:37:55.893
- Let's go!
- Move up on my six.

820
00:37:55.929 --> 00:37:58.996
- Let's go.
- Follow 'em up. Go. go. go.

821
00:37:59.032 --> 00:38:00.198
Go. Go. go.

822
00:38:00.234 --> 00:38:01.865
Here we go.

823
00:38:01.901 --> 00:38:04.603
- Freeze!
- FBI! See those hands!

824
00:38:05.672 --> 00:38:07.905
Go!

825
00:38:07.941 --> 00:38:09.372
- Nothing.
- Nothing. nothing.

826
00:38:09.408 --> 00:38:12.443
Hey. hey.

827
00:38:15.248 --> 00:38:16.379
Eyes open.

828
00:38:16.415 --> 00:38:18.048
FBI! Put your hands up!

829
00:38:18.084 --> 00:38:20.217
- Don't move! Do it now! Now!
- Hands up!

830
00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:22.286
Get down!

831
00:38:23.356 --> 00:38:24.821
Down!

832
00:38:24.857 --> 00:38:27.157
- Let's go.
- Take him downstairs.

833
00:38:27.193 --> 00:38:28.458
We're all clear. sir.

834
00:38:28.494 --> 00:38:31.027
I want every container
opened and searched.

835
00:38:31.063 --> 00:38:32.596
Wells is somewhere on board. Find her.

836
00:38:32.632 --> 00:38:33.930
- Yes. sir.
- Let's go!

837
00:38:33.966 --> 00:38:35.265
Let's get them down there now.

838
00:38:35.301 --> 00:38:37.000
Man: On the ground!

839
00:38:39.672 --> 00:38:42.538
[Indistinct shouting]

840
00:38:42.574 --> 00:38:43.806
[Groans]

841
00:38:43.842 --> 00:38:46.242
[Metal clanging]

842
00:38:51.316 --> 00:38:52.448
[Indistinct shouting]

843
00:38:52.484 --> 00:38:53.850
This one's clear!

844
00:38:58.190 --> 00:39:00.557
Man: All clear!

845
00:39:02.827 --> 00:39:04.259
All clear. sir.

846
00:39:04.295 --> 00:39:06.762
- Let's check the others.
- What about this one?

847
00:39:08.499 --> 00:39:09.597
It's welded shut. sir.

848
00:39:09.633 --> 00:39:10.966
Well. blow it.

849
00:39:16.473 --> 00:39:18.239
[Indistinct conversation]

850
00:39:18.275 --> 00:39:20.175
Yeah. we're set here.

851
00:39:28.619 --> 00:39:31.753
Here we go.

852
00:39:34.625 --> 00:39:35.656
Man: We're all set here.

853
00:39:38.361 --> 00:39:39.894
Let's go! Fire in the hole! Cover!

854
00:39:43.533 --> 00:39:45.166
- Go.
- Door's open.

855
00:39:56.679 --> 00:39:58.212
[Timer beeping]

856
00:40:08.057 --> 00:40:10.556
[Doors opening. closing]

857
00:40:10.592 --> 00:40:12.558
Hey. hey! On the ground right now!

858
00:40:12.594 --> 00:40:14.194
Get your hands behind your head!

859
00:40:14.230 --> 00:40:16.229
- Get on your knees!
- Get down! Now!

860
00:40:16.232 --> 00:40:20.171
- <font color="#D81D1D">Synced and corrected by VitoSilans</font> -
